  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA212-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu poruḷ muṭittut talaimakaṉoṭu vanta vāyilkaḷ vāy varavu kēṭṭa tōḻi talaimakaṭkuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante, who had heard of [his] coming from the mouth of the mediator wo had come along with HIM agter having accomplished wealth, said to HER.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA212">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            pārvai vēṭṭuvaṉ paṭuvalai verīi</l>
<l>            neṭuṅkāṟ kaṇantuḷam pulampuko ṭeḷviḷi</l>
<l>            curañcel koṭiyar katumeṉa vicaikku</l>
<l rend="indent4">curañcel vampalar tuṇṇeṉa vicaikku</l>
<l>narampoṭu koḷḷu mattat tāṅkaṭ     matta nīḷiṭaic ceṉṟōr nattuṟantu</l>
<l>            kaṭuṅkuraṟ pampaik katanāy vaṭukar </l>
<l>            neṭumperuṅ kuṉṟa nīnti namvayiṉ</l>
<l>            vantaṉar vāḻi tōḻi kaitai</l>
<l>            cempoṟ kaḻaṟoṭi nōkki māmakaṉ</l>
<l>            kavavukko ḷiṉkural kēṭṭoṟu</l>
<l>            mavavukkoṇ maṉattē mākiya namakkē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>He has come to us, oh friend,</l>
<l rend="indent2">crossing the long big hills</l>
<l rend="indent">of the Vaṭukar with angry dogs [and] fierce-voiced Pampai drums,</l>
<l rend="indent4">there on the road,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the clear sound full of loneliness of the long-legged Kaṇantuḷ bird,</l>
<l rend="indent2">after being frightened by the net laid out by the [sharp-]sighted<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pārvai</term> is explained by T.V.G. as a decoy bird, a tame animal put by or in the net to attract others. There is no trace of such a notion in the rest of the poem, and the word can as well be analysed as an abstract noun of <term xml:lang="ta">pār</term>, often used to describe the lookout of the hunter for his/its prey.</note> hunter,</l>
<l rend="indent">takes up<note place="foot">How <term xml:lang="ta">koḷḷum</term> goes along with an instrumental, <term xml:lang="ta">narampoṭu</term>, is not clear. We would expect a direct object.</note> the [bow]string that the desert-going cruel ones sound quickly,</l>
<l>– to us<note place="foot">A little awkward is the quasi repetition of <term xml:lang="ta">namvayiṉ</term> - <term xml:lang="ta">namakkē</term>. We might consider taking them in a slightly different sense, namely the locative referring simply to the fact of coming back ("to us"), while the dative gives the cause ("because of us"). T.V.G., for his part, refers to the later grammatical tradition (<term xml:lang="ta">Vīracōḻiyam</term>) where the dat. marked by -<term xml:lang="ta">ē</term> is understood as a locative.</note> that are of a mind taken up with love,</l>
<l rend="indent">whenever we hear the sweet voice with an embrace</l>
<l rend="indent">of [our] big son, looking at the red-golden loosening bracelets fixed</l>
<l rend="indent2">to [our] hands.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kai tai</term>: here the traditional (and better attested) reading is <term xml:lang="ta">kaiyatai</term>, which does not make much sense. T.V.G. explains it as <term xml:lang="ta">kaiyatu</term>, an untypical genitive in a very untypical position, plus an expletive <term xml:lang="ta">ai</term>.</note></l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="3+4v"><note place="foot">This is the version given by ET alone, and it certainly reads more smoothly - I do not know whether this is an argument for or against it.</note>
    <l>having abandoned [us], the one that had gone the long way</l>
    <l>on the road, where the clear sound ... suddenly sounds</l>
	<l>to the desert-going travellers.</l>
</lg>
        </lg>
      </div>
